 Abstract 
 This paper reviews some idea-based issues having to do with the (putting into) use of an clear "(related to space or existing in space)" (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important) in 
 applied econometrics. It provides an summary of the reason for including (related to space or existing in space) effects in moving backward models, both from a 
 explanation-driven as well as from a data-driven (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important). (large/relatively large) attention is paid to the guess-related (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) necessary 
 to carry out guess and testing and the different ideas (you think are true), restrictions and effects/results/suggestions deeply set within  the different 
 (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) available in the books. The review combines ideas from the usual (related to space or existing in space) econometrics books as 
 well as from geostatistics, biostatistics and medical image analysis. 
