 1. Introduction 
 The last few years have seen a virtual explosion in the 
 application of (related to space or existing in space) models in a range of fields in the 
 social sciences in general, and in applied money flow/money-based studies in 
 particular (recent reviews are given in, e.g. Anselin and 
 Bera, 1998; Goodchild et al., 2000; Anselin, 2001b,c). 
 Over time, the way(s) of doing things of (related to space or existing in space) econometrics 
 (Paelinck and Klaassen, 1979; Anselin, 1988) has matured and changed from an aspect of (related to space or existing in space) statistics 
 with first (or most important) application in (related to a large area) science and (related to careful studying or deep thinking) (the study of (or the location of) mountains, rivers, hills, etc.) (Ord, 1975; Cliff and Ord, 1981), 
 to an more and more visible thread in formal econometric explanation (for example, Conley, 1999; Kelejian and 
 Prucha, 1999, 2001; Baltagi and Li, 2001; Lee, 2002). 
