 2. Explanation-driven (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) 
 Including (related to space or existing in space) effects in applied econometric models is usually (gave a reason to do something) either on possible grounds, following from the formal (detailed description of exactly what is required) 
 of (related to space or existing in space) interaction in an money-based model, or on 
 practical grounds, due to weird qualities of the data used 
 in an scientific analysis. I think about/believe the possible 
 (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important) first. 
 In their description of the definition of (related to space or existing in space) 
 econometrics, Paelinck and Klaassen (1979) stressed 
 the importance of (related to space or existing in space) (dependent on each other), the unevenness of (related to space or existing in space) relations, and the relevance of factors 
 located in "other spaces". This early creation 
 of the importance of (related to space or existing in space) interaction was mostly 
 based on practical grounds. However, more (not very long ago), these concerns are also reflected in possible 
 money-based models of interacting agents and social 
 interaction. Such models deal with questions of how 
 the interaction between money-based agents can lead to 
 newly-seen total behavior and group patterns, 
 and they assign a central role to location, space and 
 (related to space or existing in space) interaction. The (enough to be meaningful) ideas receive 
 different labels in different subfields, such as social 
 normal behaviors, neighborhood effects, (group of same-age people) effects, respect, (related to a plan to reach a goal) interaction, copy-catting, yardstick competition and race to the bottom, to name 
 a few. However, an important (something in common) is the 
 need to formally specify the range and strength of 
 the relations between the interacting agents, which in 
 scientific practice translates into the need to specify 
 a structure for (related to space or existing in space) relationship. 
 Examples of such possible (solid basic structures on which bigger things can be built) in money flow/money-based studies are models of complex behavior built on 
 ways of thinking/basic truths/rules from (related to studying numbers) mechanics, such as interacting particle systems and random field models (Brock 
 and Durlauf, 1995; Akerlof, 1997; Durlauf, 1997); 
 macroeconomic models with mean field interaction 
 (Aoki, 1996); models for neighborhood spillover 
 
