 and a discussion of guess and identification 
 issues can be found in Cook and Pocock (1983), 
 Mardia and Marshall (1984), Dubin (1988, 1992), 
 Dubin et al. (1999), and Anselin (2001a), among 
 others. 
 In contrast, using an object view and corresponding (something made of crossed strips of wood, metal, etc.) model, the covariance structure follows indirectly from the (detailed description of exactly what is required) of the (related to space or existing in space) weights 
 matrix that underlies a (related to space or existing in space) process model (Markov 
 random field). Different (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) for the weights 
 
 L. Anselin / Farming-based Money flow 27 (2002) 247-267 
 
 and their results are reviewed in the rest 
 of this section. 
 Before going ahead with this, it is worthwhile to 
 briefly think about/believe a third way of very big structure, referred to in the books as (related to space or existing in space) error parts/pieces. 
 The full covariance structure follows from rotting the error term into parts/pieces and forcing (on people) a 
 model for the variance and covariance of these terms. 
 This approach is common in (related to certain things being ranked above or below other things) and multilevel modeling, where one error part is association with a model for (excess) mixed-up nature and 
 the other with a model for (related to space or existing in space) difference/different version, following the suggestion of Besag et al. (1991). Examples 
 of including (related to space or existing in space) random effects in (related to certain things being ranked above or below other things) Bayesian models in biostatistics are reviewed 
 in, among others, Waller et al. (1997a,b) and Best 
