 closeness, different weights structures may result for 
 the same (related to space or existing in space) layout. In the classic example of a regular square grid layout, the options are referred to as 
 the rook case (only common edges), the church supervisor 
 case (only common highest points) and the queen case (both 
 edges and highest points). Depending on the judging requirement 
 chosen, a location will have either four (rook, church supervisor) 
 or eight (queen) neighbors on average (apart from edge 
 effects). This hints quite different covariance structures for the connected random processes. Even in irregular (related to space or existing in space) layouts, a decision must be made as to 
 whether units that only share a common highest point should 
 be thought about/believed to be neighbors (queen) or not (rook). 
 In practice, the construction of the neighbor structure of irregular (related to space or existing in space) units is based on the digital 
 edge files in a GIS. Sloppiness in the storage 
 of the polygons and highest points can cause problems in 
 this respect, cooperating with/producing/giving up "islands" or other unexpected 
 friendliness structures when getting/taking the (related to space or existing in space) arrangement from these edge-related files.24 
 A second type of problem happens when the (related to space or existing in space) 
 weights are based on a distance judging requirement, such that 
 two units i and j are defined as neighbors when the 
 distance between them (or, for areal units, the distance 
 between their centroids) is less than a given critical 
 value. When there is a high degree of mixed-up nature 
 in the (related to space or existing in space) distribution of points or in the areas of 
 areas, there may be no acceptable critical distance. 
 In those events, a "small" distance will tend to produce 
 a lot of islands (or, unconnected (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements)). Also, a 
